%N A389556 The number of primitive Pythagorean triples (PPTs) that lie within the first n rows of an irregular triangular array of PPTs defined in comments and whose even leg of the integer right triangle formed from the PPT is greater than its odd leg.
%C A389556 The irregular triangular array of PPTs is generated by taking odd numbers k > 1 in sequence and generating all partitions of these odd numbers into ordered pairs (x,y) such that k = x+y, x > y and GCD(x,y) = 1.
%C A389556 The PPTs shown below is an irregular triangle sequenced by reading it by rows. The ordered pairs are sorted by k = x+y and then by x. The length of n-th row is given by phi(2n+1)/2 (see comments A072451). This array will create all possible PPTs as the number of rows tends to infinity.
%C A389556  n   k = 2n+1 = x+y             Ordered pairs (x,y)
%C A389556 ===  ==============             ===================
%C A389556  1     3                            (2,1)
%C A389556  2     5                         (3,2) (4,1)
%C A389556  3     7                      (4,3) (5,2) (6,1)
%C A389556  4     9                      (5,4) (7,2) (8,1)
%C A389556  5     11               (6,5) (7,4) (8,3) (9,2) (10,1)
%C A389556  6     13           (7,6) (8,5)  (9,4) (10,3) (11,2) (12,1)
%C A389556  7     15                 (8,7) (11,4) (13,2) (14,1)
%C A389556  8     17   (9,8) (10,7) (11,6) (12,5) (13,4) (14,3) (15,2) (16,1)
%C A389556  .      .                           .
%C A389556  .      .                           .
%C A389556 Each ordered pair (x,y) generates a PPT as (x^2-y^2, 2*x*y, x^2+y^2).
%C A389556 Empirically, the limit of a(n) / Sum_{m=1..n} phi(2*m+1)/2 tends to sqrt(2)-1 (A188582).
%e A389556 For a(5) = 6, rows 1 to 5 generate a sample of 14 ordered pairs. The 6 pairs counted are (2,1), (3,2), (4,3), (5,4), (6,5) and (7,4) and they generate PPTs (3,4,5), (5,12,13), (7,24,25), (9,40,41), (11,60,61), (33,56,65) where the even leg is greater than its odd leg.
%t A389556 get[n_] := Module[{lst = IntegerPartitions[n, {2}]}, Sort@Select[lst, OddQ[Total@#]&&GCD@@#==1&&#[[1]]/#[[2]]<1+Sqrt[2]&]]; Table[Total@Table[Length@get[2m+1], {m, 1, n}], {n, 1, 150}]
